@Node What " Introduction"


 -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Since the Amiga_E language in now freeware and at the moment (and during the last years) I've been too short on time to improve ECT *and* i didn't got any registration - that's was also important :| - I've decided to release the full version of this program as freeware, but there will be (very likely) no futher improvements, maybe only a few bug fixing perhaps.
    Still, if you're feeling generous, be my guest ...
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

      As you surely know, the Amiga_E is a case sensitive programming language so @{B}E-Case Tool (ECT)@{UB} born (a long, long time ago), because I would like to type in Amiga_E always in lower case, since I @{" was " link Unix} very lazy to keep hitting always the [Shift] key 8-) .


      So, ECT tries to make the Amiga_E case insensitive ...
      What does this means ??


      Well, it allows you to write code like this :

            proc main()
            writef('boo !')
            endproc

      and it will be translated by magic in to the E standard :

            PROC main()
            WriteF('boo !')
            ENDPROC

Wow ! Isn't that great ?! At least I think so.

And does it *really* works ?
Well @{" ... " link Limitations}
@EndNode
@Node Limitations " Limitations"


      Well, it's very difficult (impossible ?) to turn a case dependent language like Amiga_E into an 100% insensible one.
So, you still have to obey the following rules :(

Errh ... See also the @{" Bugs "link Bugs} section ... 

      * All assembly instructions must be typed in UPPER case;

      * Variables cannot have the same name of E statements or instructions;
         ( like defining the following : DEF write )   @{" HINT " link Salvation}

      * All constants must stay in UPPER case too;

      * Module calls must be also typed as previously;



