@Node Bugs " Bugs "


      There are some know bugs :


       BUG: » typing 'new' is always converted into 'NEW'
  SOLUTION:    type 'New' when you want New() or 'NEW' for the other case

       BUG: » typing 'raise' is always converted into 'RAISE'
  SOLUTION:    type 'Raise' when you want Raise() or 'RAISE' for the other

       BUG: » 'gadget' is not converted
  SOLUTION:     This one is on purpose, otherwise when you use the object
                gadget.xxx you would get Gadget.xxx ... The correct bug
                fixing to do would be to search for the string 'gadget.'and
                leave it alone, but again, this fixing would possibly never
                take place in the near future.
 
       BUG: » Let suppose you create a proc called 'intaaaa()'. It's
              then (bugly) converted into 'Intaaaa()' due to the similarity
              to Int() ... Argh !!!
  SOLUTION:    Preceed the name to your proc by a '_', that is, you would
               have to call it _intaaaa()

       BUG: » Using the character * inside a /* */ comment nest results in
		  a existencial confusion to ECT ...     
  SOLUTION:    Don't use it, please


Ok, I think it's all for now.

   Remember that the only job of ECT is to convert the case of the source, so if your program crashes and ECT seemed to work ok, be sure that you didn't do something illegal on E, 'cause my program don't do miracles ;)

   ECaseTool v1.01 never crashed during operation, but even if it crashes some day, remember that you first type and *save* your .ec source and then my program (ECT) converts it into .e, so you never loose your .ec source.

And if ECT keeps crashing with that .ec source, all you have to do is to manually retype it to the standard Amiga_E format ... Boring, but at least you don't loose your work !

@EndNode

@Node Usage " How do I "


Let's go straigth to the point:

      1· Write your program
      2· Save it with an .ec extension  (example: fly.ec)
      3· Use this program like this:

            ECT fly.ec

      Then, the ECT will create a fly.e file ('cased') and then invoke the EC itself (maybe it's wiser to put EC on the C: dir...)

      You may include some extra arguments that will be passed to the EC compiler. Example:

           ECT debug fly.ec



That's all!!
@EndNode

